          <p class='first-para'>
            I am not very happy. First, the Minister has explained clearly what will happen if a closure ratification notice is issued. If I understand him correctly, it is still the intention that the Office of Rail Regulation will issue the notice, and it will not be subject to any parliamentary procedure.</p><p>
            Let us take, for example, a proposal to close a railway line in England. I have a lot of confidence in Scottish Ministers, Welsh Ministers and the passenger transport executives&#x2014;although I may have less confidence in the Mayor of London, we are not likely to close any railways there&#x2014;but I do not have that confidence in the Secretary of State's organisation. As far as I can see, the decision will be made by the Secretary of State, but I am not sure at what juncture any parliamentary representations can be made, other than through the medium of Questions. We know that that is a slightly unsatisfactory method of eliciting information from Ministers, even if one gets a direct reply in the House of Commons.</p><p>
            <a class='permalink column-permalink' id='column_316gc' title='Col. 316GC &mdash; HL Deb 09 March 2005 vol 670 c316GC' name='column_316gc' href='#column_316gc' rel='bookmark'>316GC</a>
